Hello,

When defining a cache group where the `name` refers to an existing chunk, there is a validation check done to ensure that the existing chunk is a parent of all selected chunks being considered in the cache group.

The [code is here](https://github.com/webpack/webpack/blob/main/lib/optimize/SplitChunksPlugin.js#L1087) but I'll paste the interesting section for reference:

```
// Module can only be moved into the existing chunk if the existing chunk
// is a parent of all selected chunks
let isInAllParents = true;
/** @type {Set<ChunkGroup>} */
const queue = new Set();
for (const chunk of selectedChunks) {
    for (const group of chunk.groupsIterable) {
        queue.add(group);
    }
}
for (const group of queue) {
    if (existingChunk.isInGroup(group)) continue;
    let hasParent = false;
    for (const parent of group.parentsIterable) {
        hasParent = true;
        queue.add(parent);
    }
    if (!hasParent) {
        isInAllParents = false;
    }
}
```

If it finds that the existing chunk is not in the same group as a selected chunk, it then looks at **all** of the parent groups and it will only succeed if every one of those parent groups contains the existing chunks.

Is this intentional?  It seems quite a high bar to say that a chunk must belong to every single parent group.  Isn't belonging to one parent enough?  If I understand, that should be enough to ensure the existing chunk gets loaded before the selected chunk.

I'm wondering if that `continue` should actually be a `break` instead?

